strophic elements of the global social order emerging in the twenty-first century. By emphasizing the texture of political action, the book theorizes how social context becomes evident on the surface of events and analyzes the performative dimensions of political experience. The attention to catastrophe allows for an understanding of how ordinary people contend with normal system operation once it is indistinguishable from system breakdown. Through an array of case studies, the book provides an account of change as it is experienced, negotiated, and resisted in specific settings that define a society’s capacity for political action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aPolitical culturevCross-cultural studies. 0aPolitical participationvCross-cultural studies. 0aPolitics and culturevCross-cultural studies. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspects. 0aSocial actionvCross-cultural studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aactivism.  aanalysis.  aanthropology.  acapitalism.  acase studies.  acatastrophe.  acatastrophic elements.  aculture.  ademocracy.  aengaging.  aevolution.  agenerational.  ahistorical.  ahistory.  ahuman condition.  ahumanities.  alifetime.  amodern world.  anormal system.  aordinary people.  aperformative dimensions.  apolitical action.  apolitical culture.  apolitical experience.  apolitical science.  apolitical.  arevolution.  arhetoric.  asocial changes.  asocial context.  asocial issues.  asocial order.  asocial sciences.  asociety.  atheoretical.1 aBoromisza-Habashi, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCintron, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCintron, Ralph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 